.TH HSH 1 "2025" "Holberton School" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
hsh \- simple UNIX command line interpreter
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B hsh
[\fIscript_file\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B hsh
is a simple UNIX shell written in C as part of the Holberton School curriculum.
It reads commands from standard input or from a script file and executes them.
.PP
.B hsh
supports both interactive and non-interactive modes. In interactive mode,
a prompt
.RB ( $ )
is displayed and the shell waits for user input. In non-interactive mode,
commands are read from a pipe or script file without displaying a prompt.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B script_file
If a filename is provided as an argument,
.B hsh
reads and executes commands from that file instead of standard input,
then exits.
.SH BUILTINS
.TP
.B exit [n]
Exit the shell. If the optional argument
.I n
is given, it is used as the exit status. If no argument is given,
the exit status of the last command is used.
.TP
.B env
Print the current environment to standard output. Each variable is
printed in the form
.IR NAME=value ,
one per line.
.TP
.B cd [dir]
Change the current working directory to
.IR dir .
If no argument is given,
.B cd
changes to the directory specified by the
.B HOME
environment variable.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Interactive mode
.nf
$ ./hsh
($) /bin/ls
hsh main.c shell.c
($) echo Hello
Hello
($) exit
$
.fi
.SS Non-interactive mode
.nf
$ echo "/bin/ls" | ./hsh
hsh main.c shell.c
.fi
.SS Script file
.nf
$ cat commands.txt
/bin/ls
/bin/pwd
$ ./hsh commands.txt
hsh main.c shell.c
/home/karen/holbertonschool-simple_shell
.fi
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B PATH
A colon-separated list of directories in which
.B hsh
searches for commands. If a command is not found in any directory
listed in
.BR PATH ,
an error is printed and the exit status is set to 127.
.TP
.B HOME
Used by
.B cd
when no directory argument is given.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
General error.
.TP
.B 126
The command was found but could not be executed.
.TP
.B 127
The command was not found.
